  <brief_title>Barrier Function and Production of Inflammatory Cytokines in the Rectal Mucosa in Patients With Septic Shock</brief_title>
  <official_title>Barrier Function and Production of Inflammatory Cytokines in the Rectal Mucosa in Patients With Septic Shock</official_title>
  <sponsors>
    <lead_sponsor>
      <agency>Herlev Hospital</agency>
      <agency_class>Other</agency_class>
    </lead_sponsor>
  </sponsors>
  <source>Herlev Hospital</source>
  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Life-threatening infection impairs bloodflow to the gut, thereby causing less delivery of
      oxygen. This leads to increased formation of different inflammatory and infectious markers.

      The investigators hypothesize, therefore, that there is a significant difference in the
      concentrations of inflammatory and infectious markers in the rectal mucosa between patients
      with septic shock and healthy controls.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
